<div class="jumbotron">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="display-3">FlowCore</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A multi purpose, extendable, Workflow-net-based workflow engine for Rails applications.
    </p>
    <p class="lead mb-4">
      This is the dummy app for FlowCore, it's provides some simple cases for evaluation.
      Please make sure you have ran `rails db:seed` that import demo data.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- Example row of columns -->
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-4">
      <h2>PetriNet Definition</h2>
      <p>
        Workflow composed by ActiveRecord models, CRUD them is same as common Rails-way.
        On the page, you can see Places, Transitions and a diagram visualization,
        and try to do some configuration.
      </p>
      <p>
        <%= link_to "Try »", workflows_path, class: "btn btn-secondary" %>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-4">
      <h2>Pipeline Definition</h2>
      <p>
        PetriNet are not easy to understanding and verification,
        Pipeline is a high-level workflow definition abstraction that aim to easy to understanding for humans, easy to implement visual designer and easy to verification.
        Pipeline can be compiled to PetriNet,
        the relation between Pipeline and PetriNet is like ActiveRecord and Arel.
      </p>
      <p>
        <%= link_to "Try »", pipelines_path, class: "btn btn-secondary" %>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-4">
      <h2>Instance</h2>
      <p>
        Listing all workflow instances that you created (via definition page),
        showing them internal states to learn how Petri-net workflow works.
      </p>
      <p>
        <%= link_to "Try »", instances_path, class: "btn btn-secondary" %>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <hr>
</div>
